  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "SPP asset registration resource types valid",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "SPP",
      "data_type": "report",
      "year_start": 2020,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": "gte"
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "a3fd538d-caab-43f9-8d69-86a260313fdd",
        "score": 0.4735897,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit discusses the distribution of 89 resource owners registered to participate in the Integrated Marketplace as of December 31, 2021. It includes a pie chart (Figure 2-2) illustrating the breakdown of resource owners by type:\n\n- Independent power producers: 56\n- Investor-owned utilities: 8\n- Cooperatives: 7\n- Municipal: 6\n- Marketer: 6\n- State agency: 3\n- Industrial: 1\n- Federal agency: 1\n- Agent: 1\n\nThe text explains that the high number of independent power producers is largely due to the inclusion of most wind producers in this category. The term \"agent\" refers to several individual resource owners who would otherwise be classified under different types such as municipal utilities, electric cooperatives, and state agencies.\n\nAdditionally, the document notes that Figure 2-3 (not shown on this page) presents the generation nameplate capacity owned by each type of market participant. It highlights that investor-owned utilities and cooperatives together own 54 percent of the nameplate generation capacity in the SPP market.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_42.jpg",
          "page_num": 42,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "cd7d3efb-1954-4147-a1bb-293f70eb925c",
        "score": 0.46179408,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) provides an executive summary focused on resource accreditation and incentive mechanisms for capacity.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Policy Approval and Methodology Filing**: \n   - In July 2022, the SPP Board of Directors approved a policy paper recommended by SPP and approved by relevant committees for performance-based accreditation (PBA) of conventional resources. This uses a demand-weighted probabilistic equivalent forced outage rate demand (EFORd) variant.\n   - SPP filed this methodology, along with a modified effective load carrying capability (ELCC) methodology for variable energy resources, with FERC in February 2024.\n   - The MMU filed comments on this in late March 2024.\n\n2. **Improvements and Follow-up Items**:\n   - Using PBA and ELCC for resource accreditation is an improvement over the previous system and a first step toward better resource accreditation.\n   - However, follow-up issues remain, such as:\n     - Weighting of performance-based accredited resources during peak hours.\n     - Treatment of outages beyond management control for variable energy resources using ELCC.\n   - The MMU recommends continued work on these follow-up initiatives to improve resource adequacy and ensure non-discriminatory treatment of resources.\n\n3. **Incentive Mechanisms for Accredited Capacity (WWE2)**:\n   - The MMU emphasizes the need for both market and non-market mechanisms to incentivize resource attributes that improve reliability through resiliency and availability.\n   - It recommends developing incentives for \"reliability attributes\" alongside accurate measurements of resource availability.\n   - These two components form part of a \"three-legged stool\" ensuring reliability through measurements, incentives, and requirements.\n   - The MMU proposed market mechanisms to encourage existing resources to increase availability and efficiently schedule maintenance outages by valuing capacity availability when needed.\n   - Assigning a value to availability allows participants to make economic decisions to improve resource attributes based on resource type, location, and policy considerations.\n\nThe page also includes references to the SPP Board of Directors action, the FERC docket, and MMU comments related to these filings.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2023/page_31.jpg",
          "page_num": 31,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET 2023",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1ffbb346-ee29-4818-bcee-c75d0fffe17a",
        "score": 0.45361692,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report discusses the growth of dispatchable demand response resources in the SPP market up to December 1, 2019, and beyond. It includes a figure (Figure 2-25) that illustrates the number of demand response resources and their nameplate capacity (in MW) by year from 2019 to 2021.\n\nKey points include:\n- In 2019, three demand response resources became active, contributing 0.3 MW of capacity.\n- In 2020, 30 additional resources were added, with capacities ranging from 0.1 MW to 20 MW.\n- In 2021, 69 more resources were added, representing 143.8 MW of nameplate capacity.\n- By December 31, 2021, there were 102 demand response resources in the SPP market, totaling 176.2 MW of nameplate capacity.\n\nThe page also mentions that Figure 2-26 (not shown) will present the total generation of dispatchable demand response resources monthly for 2021 and annual totals for the past three years. The overall trend shows significant growth in both the number and capacity of demand response resources in the SPP market over the three-year period.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_64.jpg",
          "page_num": 64,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1d6f7a23-2eaf-4db8-a332-92359ab7df9a",
        "score": 0.44865435,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) discusses recommendations related to resource accreditation and capacity incentives to improve system reliability.\n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Resource Accreditation Improvements**:\n   - The SPP Board of Directors approved a policy in July 2022 for performance-based accreditation (PBA) of conventional resources using a demand-weighted probabilistic equivalent forced outage rate demand (EFORd).\n   - SPP filed this methodology, along with a modified effective load carrying capability (ELCC) method for variable energy resources, with FERC in February 2024.\n   - The MMU filed comments on this in March 2024.\n   - These new accreditation methods represent an improvement over the previous system but still require follow-up, particularly regarding weighting PBA accredited resources during peak hours and handling out-of-management control outages for variable energy resources.\n   - The MMU urges SPP and stakeholders to continue working on these follow-up initiatives to improve resource adequacy and ensure non-discriminatory treatment.\n\n2. **Incentive Mechanism for Accredited Capacity (WWE2)**:\n   - The MMU emphasizes the need for both market and non-market mechanisms to incentivize resource attributes that enhance reliability through resiliency and availability.\n   - It recommends developing incentives for \"reliability attributes\" alongside accurate measurement of resource availability.\n   - These two components form part of a three-legged approach to ensure reliability through measurements, incentives, and requirements.\n   - The MMU proposed market mechanisms to encourage existing resources to increase availability and efficiently schedule maintenance outages by valuing capacity availability when needed.\n\nThe page also includes references to relevant SPP Board actions, FERC docket filings, and MMU comments for further context.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2023/page_257.jpg",
          "page_num": 257,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET 2023",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6fe80c17-b6aa-4b77-9add-c91ab7191292",
        "score": 0.44160753,
        "text": "This document page from Southwest Power Pool, Inc.'s Market Monitoring Unit provides a summary table of various recommendations made over several years, their report years, and their current implementation status.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- Recommendations are listed by a unique identifier (e.g., 2017.1, 2015.1) along with a brief description.\n- The report years range from 2014 to 2017.\n- The current status column details whether the recommendation has been implemented, is part of the SPP Roadmap initiative, awaiting implementation, or has other specific updates.\n- Notably, the recommendation to \"Develop ramping product\" from 2017 was implemented in 2022 and is marked complete.\n- Several 2017 recommendations related to unit commitment logic, energy storage design, self-scheduling reduction, and wind scheduling are part of the ongoing SPP Roadmap initiative.\n- The 2015 recommendation on transitioning non-dispatchable variable energy resources to dispatchable status was accepted by FERC in April 2019, with a deadline for certain resources set for January 1, 2021.\n- Some 2014 recommendations, such as improving quick-start logic and addressing manipulation of make-whole payment provisions, are still awaiting implementation.\n- Another 2014 recommendation regarding day-ahead must offer requirements and physical withholding is also part of the SPP Roadmap initiative.\n\nOverall, the page provides a clear status update on various market-related recommendations, highlighting progress, ongoing initiatives, and pending actions.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_292.jpg",
          "page_num": 292,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

